## Diagnosis

The symptom — active label appearing on the **right** of the rail, hover labels appearing on the **left** — points to a classic **coordinate-system mismatch** combined with a **positioning-origin confusion**.

### What's actually happening

When you measure the notch container's `getBoundingClientRect()` and set `left: rect.left` (or `right: rect.right`), you're using **viewport-relative coordinates** on an element that is positioned relative to its **`position: fixed` or `position: absolute` ancestor** — not the viewport root. If the scroll-spy label is a sibling of the tick marks (inside the rail), `left` is measured from the rail's own origin, so the label shoots off to the right edge. If it's outside the rail, the wrong anchor gives you a different wrong number.

The hover labels work because they are styled with **`right: 100%`** (or equivalent) — a purely relative offset from their own parent — so they always hug the left edge of the rail regardless of viewport position. The active label is using an **absolute pixel value derived from a `getBoundingClientRect()` call** (AP-072: mixing viewport-space measurements with element-space positioning origins), which only coincidentally works at zero scroll and zero layout shift.

### Root cause — AP-072

> **Mixing viewport-coordinate measurements with element-relative positioning origins.** `getBoundingClientRect()` returns values in the viewport coordinate space. Assigning those values directly to `top`/`left` CSS properties is only valid when the positioned ancestor is the viewport itself (i.e., `position: fixed` with no transformed ancestor). Any other container invalidates the math.

---

## Fix

The correct model: **make the active label a sibling of the hover labels** and drive it with the same `right: 100%` + `top` offset that the hover labels use. Kill all `getBoundingClientRect`-driven `left` assignments entirely.

### File tree

```
src/
  components/
    ScrollSpy/
      ScrollSpy.tsx          ← orchestrator
      ScrollSpyRail.tsx      ← the vertical rail
      ScrollSpyLabel.tsx     ← shared label component  (new or refactored)
      scrollspy.css          ← or Tailwind @layer
```

---

### `ScrollSpyLabel.tsx` — one component, both states

```tsx
// src/components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyLabel.tsx
import React from 'react'
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils'

interface ScrollSpyLabelProps {
  label: string
  /** fractional position along the rail, 0–1 */
  offset: number
  /** total rail height in px — passed from parent so label can self-position */
  railHeight: number
  isActive?: boolean
  isHovered?: boolean
}

export function ScrollSpyLabel({
  label,
  offset,
  railHeight,
  isActive = false,
  isHovered = false,
}: ScrollSpyLabelProps) {
  const visible = isActive || isHovered

  return (
    <span
      aria-hidden="true"
      className={cn(
        // ─── Layout anchor: RIGHT edge of this span = LEFT edge of rail ───
        // This is identical to how hover labels already work.
        'absolute right-full',          // <-- THE KEY LINE
        'top-0',                         // baseline; translateY does the work
        'pr-3',                          // gutter between label and rail
        'whitespace-nowrap',
        'text-xs font-medium tracking-wide',
        'transition-opacity duration-150',
        isActive
          ? 'text-foreground opacity-100'
          : 'text-muted-foreground',
        !visible && 'opacity-0 pointer-events-none',
      )}
      style={{
        // Translate vertically to sit next to its notch.
        // Using transform keeps us out of the layout flow entirely —
        // no repositioning of siblings, no reflow.
        transform: `translateY(${offset * railHeight}px)`,
      }}
    >
      {label}
    </span>
  )
}
```

**Why `right: 100%` works here:**
The label's nearest `position` ancestor is the rail (or its inner wrapper). `right: 100%` means "my right edge aligns with my parent's left edge." This is a **purely relative** measurement; it's immune to viewport position, scroll, zoom, and CSS transforms on ancestors. No `getBoundingClientRect` needed. (EAP-027: prefer relative positioning over calculated absolute coordinates whenever the anchor relationship is fixed.)

---

### `ScrollSpyRail.tsx` — remove viewport-coordinate logic

```tsx
// src/components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyRail.tsx
'use client'

import React, { useRef } from 'react'
import { ScrollSpyLabel } from './ScrollSpyLabel'
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils'

interface Section {
  id: string
  label: string
  /** 0–1 fractional position on the rail */
  offset: number
}

interface ScrollSpyRailProps {
  sections: Section[]
  activeId: string | null
}

export function ScrollSpyRail({ sections, activeId }: ScrollSpyRailProps) {
  const railRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)
  // Read rail height once; ResizeObserver keeps it fresh.
  const [railHeight, setRailHeight] = React.useState(0)

  React.useEffect(() => {
    const el = railRef.current
    if (!el) return
    const ro = new ResizeObserver(([entry]) => {
      setRailHeight(entry.contentRect.height)
    })
    ro.observe(el)
    return () => ro.disconnect()
  }, [])

  const [hoveredId, setHoveredId] = React.useState<string | null>(null)

  return (
    <div
      ref={railRef}
      // The rail must be `relative` so that `right: 100%` on children
      // is calculated from THIS element's left edge — not a distant ancestor.
      className="relative w-px bg-border self-stretch"
      // ↑ DO NOT add `overflow: hidden` here — labels live outside the rail width
    >
      {sections.map((section) => {
        const isActive = section.id === activeId
        const isHovered = section.id === hoveredId

        return (
          <React.Fragment key={section.id}>
            {/* Notch / tick */}
            <button
              aria-label={`Scroll to ${section.label}`}
              className={cn(
                'absolute left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 -translate-y-1/2',
                'w-2 h-2 rounded-full',
                'transition-colors duration-150',
                isActive
                  ? 'bg-foreground scale-125'
                  : 'bg-muted-foreground/40 hover:bg-muted-foreground',
              )}
              style={{ top: `${section.offset * 100}%` }}
              onMouseEnter={() => setHoveredId(section.id)}
              onMouseLeave={() => setHoveredId(null)}
              onClick={() => {
                document.getElementById(section.id)?.scrollIntoView({
                  behavior: 'smooth',
                  block: 'start',
                })
              }}
            />

            {/* Label — same component, same anchor, both states */}
            <ScrollSpyLabel
              label={section.label}
              offset={section.offset}
              railHeight={railHeight}
              isActive={isActive}
              isHovered={isHovered}
            />
          </React.Fragment>
        )
      })}
    </div>
  )
}
```

---

### `scrollspy.css` — guard against the overflow clip trap

```css
/* src/components/ScrollSpy/scrollspy.css  (or inside @layer components) */
@layer components {
  /*
   * The rail wrapper must NEVER clip its overflow on the inline axis.
   * Labels extend to the LEFT (right: 100%) and must be visible.
   * Overflow clipping is the silent killer of right:100% labels.
   */
  .scrollspy-rail-wrapper {
    overflow-x: visible !important;
    overflow-y: visible !important;
  }
}
```

Apply `.scrollspy-rail-wrapper` to whatever ancestor wraps the rail in your layout.

---

### What to **delete**

Search the codebase for these patterns and remove them:

```tsx
// ❌ DELETE — viewport-coordinate positioning (AP-072)
const rect = notchEl.getBoundingClientRect()
setLabelStyle({ left: rect.left, top: rect.top })

// ❌ DELETE — positioning label outside the rail then correcting with JS
labelEl.style.left = `${railRect.left - labelWidth}px`

// ❌ DELETE — any right/left value derived from getBoundingClientRect
// when the label's offsetParent is NOT document.body/null
```

---

## Principle

| # | Rule |
|---|------|
| **AP-072** | Never assign `getBoundingClientRect()` values to `top`/`left` unless the element is `position: fixed` **and** has no transformed ancestor. |
| **EAP-027** | When the spatial relationship between two elements is **fixed** (label always left of rail), encode it with a relative CSS property (`right: 100%`, `margin-inline-end`) — not with JavaScript math. |
| **CAP-016** | A single component with variant props (`isActive`, `isHovered`) is always safer than two separate components that duplicate positioning logic and inevitably diverge. |

The entire fix reduces to: **put the active label in the same coordinate system as the hover labels by making it the same element driven by the same CSS rule.**
